*=========================================================
* 10-bit Resistor-String DAC Testbench (full 1024-code sweep)
* Uses explicit hold-point PWL at every 10ns boundary for all 10
* bits (and complements) - NOT a compact/change-only PWL, since
* SPICE linearly interpolates between PWL points rather than
* holding the last value; a compact version was found to produce
* false ramps instead of clean steps for slowly-toggling bits
* (discovered and fixed during the 9-bit testbench debugging).
*
* NOTE: 10bitdac.sch was netlisted standalone, so its .subckt/.ends
* wrapper is commented out (expected xschem behavior). Sources
* attach directly to the real top-level node names already present:
* vref_top, gnda, vdd, d0..d9, d0b..d9b, v_out.
*=========================================================
.lib "/home/harshini/OpenLane/pdks/volare/sky130/versions/0fe599b2afb6708d281543108caf8310912f54af/sky130A/libs.tech/combined/sky130.lib.spice" tt

* Adjust this path to wherever xschem wrote the netlist for
* 10bitdac.sch (check with: find ~/DAC_Project -iname "10bitdac.spice")
.include "simulation/10bitdac.spice"

****************************************************
* Power / Reference
****************************************************
VVREF  vref_top  0    DC 1.8
VDD    vdd       0    DC 1.8
VGND   gnda      0    DC 0

****************************************************
* Digital Code Sweep: d9 d8 ... d1 d0 = 0..1023
* Each code held for 10ns, 1024 codes -> 10240ns total.
****************************************************

Vd0  d0  0 PWL(
+ 0n 0
+ 9.9n 0
+ 10n 1.8
+ 19.9n 1.8
+ 20n 0
+ 29.9n 0
+ 30n 1.8
+ 39.9n 1.8
